Estimation in exponential family Regression based on linked data contaminated by mismatch error

Zhenbang Wangâ‹† Â Â Â Â Â Â  Emanuel Ben-Davidâ€  Â Â Â Â Â Â  Martin Slawskiâ‹† Â Â 
â‹†Department of Statistics, George Mason University Â Â Â Â Â Â  â€ â€ \daggerU.S.Â Census, CSRM The first and the last author are partially supported by NSF award CRII: CIF: 1849876
Abstract

Identification of matching records in multiple files can be a challenging and error-prone task. Linkage error can considerably affect subsequent statistical analysis based on the resulting linked file. Several recent papers have studied post-linkage linear regression analysis with the response variable in one file and the covariates in a second file from the perspective of the â€Broken Sample Problemâ€ and â€œPermuted Dataâ€. In this paper, we present an extension of this line of research to exponential family response given the assumption of a small to moderate number of mismatches. A method based on observation-specific offsets to account for potential mismatches and â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}-penalization is proposed, and its statistical properties are discussed. We also present sufficient conditions for the recovery of the correct correspondence between covariates and responses if the regression parameter is known. The proposed approach is compared to established baselines, namely the methods by Lahiri-Larsen and Chambers, both theoretically and empirically based on synthetic and real data. The results indicate that substantial improvements over those methods can be achieved even if only limited information about the linkage process is available.



Keywords: Record linkage, Broken Sample Problem, Generalized Linear models, Penalized Estimation, Permutation

1 Introduction

A tacit assumption in regression is that response-predictor pairs correspond to the same statistical unit. In practice, this assumption is often violated at least in part when different subsets of variables are collected in an asynchronous fashion and are subsequently combined into a single data set. Roughly speaking, the latter amounts to merging multiple data sets given agreement on a set of matching variables shared across those data sets; Figure 1 serves as an illustration.

This setting is well-studied in the field of record linkage, e.g., [1, 2, 3, 4]. A principal reason for its importance is considerable potential in reducing efforts for data collection in the situation that a research question of interest can be answered simply by combining existing databases. In a nutshell, probabilistic record linkage is concerned with the identification of matching records, i.e., pieces of information contained in different data sets belonging to the same statistical unit, given only approximate identifiers. The uncertainty associated with those introduces two types of linkage errors, (i) missed matches and (ii) mismatches. The former refers to two matching records not being linked, while (ii) refers to two records erroneously linked in the sense that those records belong to different statistical units. The present work is concerned with the consequences of mismatches on subsequent regression analysis. Since the work of Neter [5] in 1965, it is well known that mismatches can negatively affect model fit and parameter estimation, specifically bearing a strong potential for attenuation bias. Following up on [5], a variety of papers discuss strategies for bias correction in linear regression with mismatches in the response variable given specific information about the linkage process, including work by Scheuren and Winkler [6, 7], Lahiri and Larsen [8] and Chambers [9]. Generalizations of this line of research beyond one-to-one matching and linear models are discussed in [10] and [11] via estimating equation-based approaches.

A somewhat more direct paradigm for dealing with mismatches in the response variable originates in the â€œBroken Sample Problemâ€, a term used in a series of papers by De Groot and collaborators, e.g., [12, 13]. In brief, mismatches are modeled via an unknown index permutation; the latter is typically regarded as a nuisance parameter, but inference for it might be of interest for the purpose of pinpointing and correcting errors in the linkage process. While this paradigm was widely regarded as infeasible in the record literature due to the combinatorial nature and the associated computational challenges, it has recently experienced a surge of interest, fueled by advances in computing and an array of engineering and machine learning problems that can be cast as linear regression with unknown permutation [14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21].

In this paper, we adopt the â€œBroken Sampleâ€ formulation for generalized linear regression models with exponential family response [22] as an alternative to the methods in Lahiri-Larsen [8, 10] and Chambers [9, 11] to account for potential mismatches in the response variable. The approach taken herein arises as a natural generalization of work by Slawski and Ben-David [23] for Gaussian response. An appealing property of the approach is that no information about the linkage process is required, in contrast to the methods put forth by Lahiri & Larsen and Chambers. This can be an important advantage if file linkage has been performed by a third party, and the data analyst is only provided the linked file, a situation that is not uncommon in practice given that file linkage is often based on sensitive personal information such as names or addresses.

In return, the number of mismatches that can be tolerated by the proposed approach is limited to at most a small linear fraction of the number of samples; while such stringent limit on the fraction of mismatches may be potentially improved upon, parameter estimation in the setting of arbitrary mismatch contamination becomes in general infeasible from both computational and statistical viewpoints [24]. Contributions. In this paper, we study the â€Broken Sampleâ€ problem, also known as â€Regression with Unknown Permutationâ€ or â€Regression with Shuffled Dataâ€, for generalized linear models. While the work herein is in the same spirit as prior work on this subject, the mechanism generating mismatches is not required to be a permutation; instead, we work with the sample-to-register linkage paradigm in [11, 25] in which the number of responses (observed sample) is allowed to be smaller than the number of predictors (contained in the register). As outlined above, primary interest concerns the regime of â€sparsely mismatchedâ€ data in which the fraction of mismatches is subject to specific limits as elaborated in the sequel. The main technical contributions herein concern (1) restoration of the correctly matching records (â€permutation recoveryâ€) for known regression parameter, (2) estimation of the regression parameter via computationally tractable schemes. In combination, (1) and (2) pave the way for â€plug-inâ€ estimation of the (generalized) permutation, thereby sidestepping the computational barriers that are associated with joint estimation. Specifically, (1) is shown to be reducible to sorting, and recovery results are derived under certain separability conditions naturally extending those for linear regression [26, 23]; regarding (2), we follow the route taken in [23] in which sparse mismatch contamination is captured by observation-specific dummy variables and â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}-penalization whose statistical analysis is based on techniques in [27]. The proposed approach is compared to the Lahiri-Larsen-type method in [10] theoretically as well as empirically by means of bike sharing data from [28]. Related work. There is a rapidly growing body of literature on regression with unknown permutation, starting from [14, 29]. The paper [29] presents necessary and sufficient conditions for permutation recovery for linear models with Gaussian design. Extensions to multivariate linear models are considered in [26, 19]. The papers [16, 24] show that consistent estimation of the regression parameter is impossible without substantial additional assumptions. Tsakiris and collaborators [20, 21] have studied important theoretical aspects such as well-posedness from an algebraic perspective, and have also put forth practical computational schemes such as a branch-and-bound algorithm (cf.Â also [30]) and concave maximization [31]. An approximate EM scheme with a Markov-Chain-Monte-Carlo (MCMC) approximation of the E-step is discussed in [17, 32]. The latter work in turn bears a relationship with the Bayesian approach in [33] and its implementation via Gibbs sampling. Approaches to linear and multivariate linear regression with sparsely mismatched data are studied in [23, 18, 34, 35].

In comparison, relatively few papers have considered regression with permuted data outside the standard linear model: examples include spherical regression [36], univariate isotonic regression and statistical seriation [37, 38, 39, 40, 41], and binary regression [42].

The method for regression parameter estimation considered herein has been studied in prior work to deal with generic contaminations in linear regression [43], logistic regression [44] and other generalized linear models [45]. Unlike the present paper, none of these works contain a rigorous statistical analysis.

Lastly, as indicated at the beginning of the introduction, there is a separate line of research focusing on parameter estimation under mismatch error in the response given at least a fair amount of knowledge about the linkage process. We refer to the surveys [10, 46]. Recovery of the underlying permutation is not considered in those works.

2 Estimation of the regression parameter

In this section, we formulate our approach for estimating the regression parameter in GLMs in the presence of mismatch error, i.e., in the setting outlined in Â§Â§\S1.1. A bound on the â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2}-estimation error of the proposed approach is presented subsequently, which is complemented by numerical results based on simulated data.

2.1 Approach

Defining oiâˆ—=(ğ±Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)âˆ’ğ±i)âŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ±superscriptğœ‹ğ‘–subscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½o_{i}^{*}=(\mathbf{x}_{\pi^{*}(i)}-\mathbf{x}_{i})^{\top}\beta^{*}, we have that yi|ğ±i,oiâˆ—conditionalsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–subscriptğ±ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–y_{i}|\mathbf{x}_{i},o_{i}^{*} follows a GLM with linear predictor Î·Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)=ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—+oiâˆ—subscriptğœ‚superscriptğœ‹ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–\eta_{\pi^{*}(i)}=\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{*}+o_{i}^{*}, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq i\leq n. Clearly, Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)=isuperscriptğœ‹ğ‘–ğ‘–\pi^{*}(i)=i implies that oiâˆ—=0superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–0o_{i}^{*}=0 and in turn Î·Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)=Î·i=ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—subscriptğœ‚superscriptğœ‹ğ‘–subscriptğœ‚ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½\eta_{\pi^{*}(i)}=\eta_{i}=\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{*}, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq i\leq n. Accordingly, the underlying idea is to a fit a generalized linear model in which each linear predictor is augmented by an individual â€œdummy variableâ€ or â€œoffsetâ€ in order to account for potential mismatches. Without additional constraints or regularization, such approach is not meaningful since it is overparameterized and trivially achieves perfect fit. However, in a sparse mismatch regime with Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)=isuperscriptğœ‹ğ‘–ğ‘–\pi^{*}(i)=i holding for all except for kğ‘˜k indices, the use of sparsity-promoting penalties like the â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}-penalty becomes a natural choice. This gives rise to the following formulation: for Î¸âˆˆâ„d+nğœƒsuperscriptâ„ğ‘‘ğ‘›\theta\in{\mathbb{R}}^{d+n}, we consider the partitioning Î¸=[Î²âŠ¤â€‹Î¾âŠ¤]âŠ¤ğœƒsuperscriptdelimited-[]superscriptğ›½topsuperscriptğœ‰toptop\theta=[\beta^{\top}\;\xi^{\top}]^{\top} with Î²âˆˆâ„dğ›½superscriptâ„ğ‘‘\beta\in{\mathbb{R}}^{d} and Î¾âˆˆâ„nğœ‰superscriptâ„ğ‘›\xi\in{\mathbb{R}}^{n}. We then consider estimation based on minimizing the penalized negative log-likelihood given by

â„“pen(Î¸)=â„“(Î¸)+Î»âˆ¥Î¾âˆ¥1,â„“(Î¸):=1n{âˆ’âŸ¨ğ—Î²+nÎ¾,ğ²âŸ©+âˆ‘i=1nÏˆ(ğ±iâŠ¤Î²+nÎ¾i)},\ell_{\text{pen}}(\theta)=\ell(\theta)+\lambda\lVert\xi\rVert_{1},\qquad\ell(\theta)\mathrel{\mathop{:}}=\frac{1}{n}\left\{-\langle\mathbf{X}\beta+\sqrt{n}\xi,\mathbf{y}\rangle+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\psi(\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta+\sqrt{n}\xi_{i})\right\}, (5)

where ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X} is the usual design matrix with rows {ğ±iâŠ¤}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topğ‘–1ğ‘›\{\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\}_{i=1}^{n}, ğ²=(yi)i=1nğ²superscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\mathbf{y}=(y_{i})_{i=1}^{n}, and Î»â‰¥0ğœ†0\lambda\geq 0 is a tuning parameter whose choice will be discussed below. In (5), the dummy variables Î¾=(Î¾i)i=1nğœ‰superscriptsubscriptsubscriptğœ‰ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\xi=(\xi_{i})_{i=1}^{n} are in correspondence to the {oiâˆ—}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{o_{i}^{*}\}_{i=1}^{n} above; re-scaling by nâˆ’1/2superscriptğ‘›12n^{-1/2} is done exclusively for technical reasons, since this choice turns out to be convenient for the theoretical analysis of (5) presented below.

Formulations of the form (5) or similar have been considered in prior work in different contexts. The use of dummy variables to deal with data contamination in linear models has been discussed in She and Owen [43], Laska et al.Â [49], Nguyen & Tran [50], and more recently in Bhatia et al.Â [51]. Extensions to generalized linear models have been proposed in [44, 45, 52]. Slawski & Ben-David [23] study and analyze this approach in detail for mismatch contamination, and the present paper arises as a direct extension of their work. It is worth emphasizing that despite prior work on the formulation (5), the latter has not been studied specifically for mismatch contamination. Moreover, none of the earlier works on [44, 45, 52] contain a complete theoretical analysis as provided herein.

We note in passing that (5) can be applied broadly in situations beyond linkage of Fğ±subscriptğ¹ğ±F_{\mathbf{x}} and Fysubscriptğ¹ğ‘¦F_{y}. For example, rather common situations are (i) a subset of the covariates is contained in the same file in the response, (ii) file linkage involves more than two files, each containing different subsets of the covariates and/or the response. Both (i) and (ii) can be addressed via (5) based on suitable choices of the variables {oiâˆ—}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{o_{i}^{*}\}_{i=1}^{n}.

2.2 Computation

There are various ways of solving the convex optimization problem (5). A particularly suitable approach that exploits structure specific to (5) is block coordinate descent with blocks formed by Î²ğ›½\beta and Î¾ğœ‰\xi, respectively. The key observation is that for any fixed value of Î²ğ›½\beta, minimization over Î¾ğœ‰\xi can be performed in closed form via a soft thresholding-type update [53]. On the other hand, note that for any fixed Î¾ğœ‰\xi minimization with respect to Î²ğ›½\beta amounts to fitting the underlying GLM with offset nâ€‹Î¾iğ‘›subscriptğœ‰ğ‘–\sqrt{n}\xi_{i} for observation iğ‘–i, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq i\leq n. Since the proposed algorithm is already iterative, alternating between updates of Î²ğ›½\beta and Î¾ğœ‰\xi, we only perform a single iteration of weighted least squares (aka Fisher Scoring) when updating Î²ğ›½\beta; this is equivalent to minimizing the quadratic Taylor approximation of the objective (with Î¾ğœ‰\xi treated as fixed) around the current iterate Î²^(t)superscript^ğ›½ğ‘¡\widehat{\beta}^{(t)}. A schematic description of the algorithm is provided below.

Given extensive numerical experience, Algorithm 1 converges in practice after few iterations. In order to establish convergence theoretically, the two updates above would need to be combined with a suitable mechanism for step size selection [54]. Since the latter is standard in the optimization literature, we refrain from discussing this aspect in detail to avoid digressions.

2.3 Incorporating blocking variables

Recall that oiâˆ—=(ğ±Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)âˆ’ğ±i)âŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ±superscriptğœ‹ğ‘–subscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½o_{i}^{*}=(\mathbf{x}_{\pi^{*}(i)}-\mathbf{x}_{i})^{\top}\beta^{*}, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq i\leq n. Note that if N=nğ‘ğ‘›N=n so that Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} is a permutation, it is easy to see that âˆ‘i=1noiâˆ—=0superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–0\sum_{i=1}^{n}o_{i}^{*}=0. As a result, the additional constraint âˆ‘i=1nÎ¾i=0superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›subscriptğœ‰ğ‘–0\sum_{i=1}^{n}\xi_{i}=0 may be added to the optimization problem (5). This simple observation can be put to much more use if Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} is known to be â€œblock-structuredâ€ in the sense that the data set can be partitioned into disjoint groups G1,â€¦,GKâŠ‚{1,â€¦,n}subscriptğº1â€¦subscriptğºğ¾1â€¦ğ‘›G_{1},\ldots,G_{K}\subset\{1,\ldots,n\} such that iâˆˆGjğ‘–subscriptğºğ‘—i\in G_{j} for some jâˆˆ{1,â€¦,K}ğ‘—1â€¦ğ¾j\in\{1,\ldots,K\} implies that Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)âˆˆGjsuperscriptğœ‹ğ‘–subscriptğºğ‘—\pi^{*}(i)\in G_{j}, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq i\leq n; in other words, the permutation only moves indices within, but not across groups. With the same reasoning as above, we then have âˆ‘iâˆˆGjoiâˆ—=0subscriptğ‘–subscriptğºğ‘—superscriptsubscriptğ‘œğ‘–0\sum_{i\in G_{j}}o_{i}^{*}=0, which accordingly yields the constraints âˆ‘iâˆˆGjÎ¾i=0subscriptğ‘–subscriptğºğ‘—subscriptğœ‰ğ‘–0\sum_{i\in G_{j}}\xi_{i}=0, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤K1ğ‘—ğ¾1\leq j\leq K, to be added to (5). Specifically, this yields the following optimization problem

minÎ¸â¡â„“â€‹(Î¸)+Î»â€‹âˆ¥Î¾âˆ¥1â€‹subject toâ€‹ğ‚â€‹Î¾=ğŸ,subscriptğœƒâ„“ğœƒğœ†subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğœ‰1subject toğ‚ğœ‰0\min_{\theta}\ell(\theta)+\lambda\lVert\xi\rVert_{1}\;\;\text{subject to}\;\mathbf{C}\xi=\mathbf{0}, (6)

where ğ‚âˆˆâ„KÃ—nğ‚superscriptâ„ğ¾ğ‘›\mathbf{C}\in{\mathbb{R}}^{K\times n} has entries Cjâ€‹i=1subscriptğ¶ğ‘—ğ‘–1C_{ji}=1 if iâˆˆGjğ‘–subscriptğºğ‘—i\in G_{j} and zero otherwise, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤K,â€‰1â‰¤iâ‰¤nformulae-sequence1ğ‘—ğ¾1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq j\leq K,\,1\leq i\leq n. In particular, in the case of singleton groups with Gj={i}subscriptğºğ‘—ğ‘–G_{j}=\{i\} for iâˆˆ{1,â€¦,n}ğ‘–1â€¦ğ‘›i\in\{1,\ldots,n\}, it immediately follows that Î¾i=0subscriptğœ‰ğ‘–0\xi_{i}=0 and the corresponding variable can be eliminated in (6). If Kğ¾K is large, this yields a substantial number of extra constraints whose integration in (6) can considerably boost performance relative to the unconstrained minimizer not taking any advantage of the block structure of Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*}. The latter arises when additional knowledge about the linkage process is available. More specifically, it is common that matching records are known to agree on certain combinations of variables present for the records in both Fğ±subscriptğ¹ğ±F_{\mathbf{x}} and Fysubscriptğ¹ğ‘¦F_{y} (e.g., demographic variables such as gender, age, and/or race, approximate geographical location based on ZIP code, approximate time stamps, etc.). Those variables are typically referred to as blocking variables, and the corresponding groups {Gj}j=1Ksuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğºğ‘—ğ‘—1ğ¾\{G_{j}\}_{j=1}^{K} are given by subsets of observations sharing the same values for all blocking variables.

In summary, while the approach (5) works without any knowledge about the linkage process and the existence of blocking variables, it is possible to achieve enhancements if such information is available. This aspect is investigated in detail in Â§Â§\S5.

with probability at least 1âˆ’Ïµnâˆ’Ïµnâ€²âˆ’2/n1subscriptitalic-Ïµğ‘›superscriptsubscriptitalic-Ïµğ‘›â€²2ğ‘›1-\epsilon_{n}-\epsilon_{n}^{\prime}-2/n.

Figure 2 confirms that as the pre-factor Cğ¶C increases, the error ratio approaches one as expected since Î¸^â†’Î¸^naiveâ†’^ğœƒsuperscript^ğœƒnaive\widehat{\theta}\rightarrow\widehat{\theta}^{\text{naive}} as Cğ¶C grows. Note that as Câ†’0â†’ğ¶0C\rightarrow 0 the proposed approach effectively yields an over-parameterized model achieving perfect fit on a given data set. This in agreement with Theorem 1 which requires a lower bound on Î»ğœ†\lambda for its results to hold. Average estimation errors for the regression parameter are shown in Figure 3. Shaded areas are used to represent the error range the for the proposed approach in dependence of the pre-factor Cğ¶C: the upper and lower margins of the shaded areas represent the maximum and minimum error over Câˆˆ[0.1,2]ğ¶0.12C\in[0.1,2], while the dashed lines outside the shaded areas indicate Â±plus-or-minus\pm5 Ã—\times standard error. Overall, Figure 3 shows that the proposed estimator can achieve substantial improvements over the naive estimator in a variety of settings. The extent of the improvement generally increases with the fraction of mismatches and the signal level as measured by âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}. For example, in the Poisson case the proposed approach with optimally calibrated Î»ğœ†\lambda roughly achieves a three-fold reduction in average estimation error over the naive solution when âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2=1subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½21\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}=1, whereas a five-fold to six-fold reduction is achieved when âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2=2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½22\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}=2. Despite the improvements that are obtained, the performance of the proposed estimator is still somewhat far from the oracle, specifically as k/nğ‘˜ğ‘›k/n increases, which indicates a potential for further reductions in error.

The results shown in Figure 4 concerning the deviance between Î¼âˆ—superscriptğœ‡âˆ—\mu^{\ast} and Î¼estsuperscriptğœ‡est\mu^{\text{est}} as explained above agree with what is expected based on the results for the estimation error in Figure 3. Again, the results indicate a dependence of the improvement achieved by the proposed estimator on the signal level and the fraction of mismatches.

Binary response. We now address the case of binary logistic regression. Note that this case behaves differently from the three distributions for the response considered above, including binomial response with a significant number of trials: it is clear that a massive number of samples is required in order to estimate Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} accurately from binary response if âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2} is large; at the same time, if âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2} is small, the separation between the two classes corresponding to the two values of the response variable is weak and thus the inherent noise is scarcely distinguishable from mismatch error in the response variable, which amounts to what has been extensively studied in the machine learning literature under the terms â€œlabel noiseâ€ (e.g., [58]). For this reason, we adopt the simulation setup above with sufficiently strong signal, i.e., âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2âˆˆ{4,6,8}subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2468\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}\in\{4,6,8\} while Î²0âˆ—=2superscriptsubscriptğ›½02\beta_{0}^{*}=2, but the three competitors are evaluated only in terms of the deviance between Î¼âˆ—superscriptğœ‡\mu^{*} and Î¼estsuperscriptğœ‡est\mu^{\text{est}}. Figure 5 shows that the proposed approach achieves improvements over the naive estimator, but the improvements are less pronounced than for the three other settings. The observed moderate improvement is in alignment with what is reported in the paper [44] that studies the empirical performance of the proposed estimator exclusively in the setting of binary response with noisy labels.

3 Permutation Recovery

In this section, we suppose throughout that N=nğ‘ğ‘›N=n and present sufficient conditions for specific GLMs under which the maximum likelihood (ML) estimator Ï€^^ğœ‹\widehat{\pi} of Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} for known Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} (4) achieves perfect recovery in the sense of {Ï€^=Ï€âˆ—}^ğœ‹superscriptğœ‹\{\widehat{\pi}=\pi^{*}\}. While the assumption of known Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} may appear limiting, the results of this section can still be useful from at least two considerations: first, it is not unreasonable to expect that they continue to be valid if Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} is replaced by an accurate estimator; second, they provide some insights into what is at best achievable in practice.

The first result states that ML estimation of Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} for known Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} is computationally tractable as already indicated in the introduction of this paper.

Proposition 1.

Consider ML estimation of Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*}, i.e., optimization problem (4) for Î²=Î²âˆ—ğ›½superscriptğ›½\beta=\beta^{*}. We then have

minÏ€âˆˆğ’«â€‹(n)âˆ’âˆ‘i=1n{yiâ€‹ğ±Ï€â€‹(i)âŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—+Ïˆâ€‹(ğ±Ï€â€‹(i)âŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—)}=minÏ€âˆˆğ’«â€‹(n)âˆ’âˆ‘i=1nyiâ€‹ğ±Ï€â€‹(i)âŠ¤â€‹Î²+c=âˆ’âˆ‘i=1ny(i)â€‹(ğ±âŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—)(i)+c,subscriptğœ‹ğ’«ğ‘›superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›subscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ±ğœ‹ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½ğœ“superscriptsubscriptğ±ğœ‹ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½subscriptğœ‹ğ’«ğ‘›superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›subscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ±ğœ‹ğ‘–topğ›½ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›subscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–subscriptsuperscriptğ±topsuperscriptğ›½ğ‘–ğ‘\min_{\pi\in\mathcal{P}(n)}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}\{y_{i}\mathbf{x}_{\pi(i)}^{\top}\beta^{*}+\psi(\mathbf{x}_{\pi(i)}^{\top}\beta^{*})\}=\min_{\pi\in\mathcal{P}(n)}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_{i}\mathbf{x}_{\pi(i)}^{\top}\beta+c=-\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_{(i)}(\mathbf{x}^{\top}\beta^{*})_{(i)}+c, (8)

where c=âˆ‘i=1nÏˆâ€‹(ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—)ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›ğœ“superscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½c=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\psi(\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{*}) and the subscript (i)ğ‘–(i) refers to the iğ‘–i-th order statistic, i.e., for v=(vi)i=1nğ‘£superscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘£ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›v=(v_{i})_{i=1}^{n}, v(1)â‰¤â€¦â‰¤v(n)subscriptğ‘£1â€¦subscriptğ‘£ğ‘›v_{(1)}\leq\ldots\leq v_{(n)}.

Proposition 1 states that the MLE Ï€^^ğœ‹\widehat{\pi} of Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} is given by the permutation that pairs the corresponding order statistics of {ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{*}\}_{i=1}^{n} and {yi}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}. For later reference, it is worth noting that the conclusion of Proposition 1 with regard to the form of Ï€^^ğœ‹\widehat{\pi} continues to hold if the link function is not the canonical link. This is an immediate consequence of the fact that Ï€^^ğœ‹\widehat{\pi} is invariant under monotonically increasing transformations of {ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{*}\}_{i=1}^{n}. The proof of Proposition 1 follows immediately from existing results in the literature on linear assignment problems (cf., e.g., [48]), and is hence omitted.

In the sequel, we refrain from presenting a unified analysis applicable to an entire class of GLMs for two reasons: first, sharper results can be obtained from case-specific analysis; second, permutation recovery turns out to be entirely or at least largely infeasible for a variety of GLMs, e.g., i) binomial response with a small number of trials due to excessive ties among the {yi}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}, ii) exponential response with canonical (i.e., reciprocal) link since in this case recovery fails for a wide range of random designs (cf.Â Theorem 3 below).

3.1 Recovery Results

We start the presentation of our results by conditioning on the predictors {ğ±i}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{\mathbf{x}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}, and hence for fixed conditional expectations of the responses. The extension to random predictors is considered subsequently.

In this subsection, it is appropriate to distinguish between random variables {Yi}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘Œğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{Y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n} and their realizations {yi}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}. Part (a) already appears in similar form in [23]. Part (b) can be linked to (a) by noting that the standard deviation of a Poisson random variable with mean Î¼ğœ‡\mu equals Î¼ğœ‡\sqrt{\mu}. Substituting Ïƒğœ\sigma in (a) by Î¼isubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–\sqrt{\mu}_{i} and dividing both sides by this quantity then approximately yields (b). Part (c) can be understood according to a similar heuristic: observing that the standard deviation of Yiâˆ¼Gammaâ€‹(Î½,Î¼i)similar-tosubscriptğ‘Œğ‘–Gammağœˆsubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–Y_{i}\sim\text{Gamma}(\nu,\mu_{i}) is given by Î¼i/Î½subscriptğœ‡ğ‘–ğœˆ\mu_{i}/\sqrt{\nu}, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n1ğ‘–ğ‘›1\leq i\leq n, substituting Ïƒğœ\sigma in (a) by Î¼isubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–\mu_{i} yields a requirement on the ratio Î¼i+1/Î¼isubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–1subscriptğœ‡ğ‘–\mu_{i+1}/\mu_{i}. Note that for Î½â‰logâ¡nasymptotically-equalsğœˆğ‘›\nu\asymp\log n, the ratios need to exceed a constant factor C>1ğ¶1C>1, which still requires Î¼n/Î¼1=Cnâˆ’1subscriptğœ‡ğ‘›subscriptğœ‡1superscriptğ¶ğ‘›1\mu_{n}/\mu_{1}=C^{n-1}. For the exponential distribution, Î½=1ğœˆ1\nu=1, and there is thus little hope that (c) can be satisfied in practice even for small nğ‘›n.

Incorporating blocking variables. Following up on the discussion in Â§Â§\S2.3, it is worth pointing out that permutation recovery based on (8) decouples across blocks, and hence can be performed in a block-by-block fashion. The recovery conditions in Theorems 2 and 3 can be applied for each block in that nğ‘›n gets replaced by the number of elements belonging to the respective block, and are thus easier to satisfy. For example, if nj=n/Ksubscriptğ‘›ğ‘—ğ‘›ğ¾n_{j}=n/K, j=1,â€¦,Kğ‘—1â€¦ğ¾j=1,\ldots,K, and Î´=Î´0/Kğ›¿subscriptğ›¿0ğ¾\delta=\delta_{0}/K for a given failure probability Î´0subscriptğ›¿0\delta_{0}, it is easy to check that all terms involving nâˆ’1ğ‘›1n-1 get replaced by n/Kâˆ’1ğ‘›ğ¾1n/K-1. This yield substantial benefits particularly if n/K=Oâ€‹(1)ğ‘›ğ¾ğ‘‚1n/K=O(1), i.e., in the case of many small blocks.

Mismatch recovery. Note that (8) does not take advantage of a sparse mismatch regime if the latter is known to hold. 3.2 Simulation

We complement Theorems 2 and 3 with simulation results. The entries of the design matrix are sampled i.i.d.Â from three unit-variance distributions: (i) standard Normal, (ii) the uniform distribution on [âˆ’3,3]33[-\sqrt{3},\sqrt{3}], and (iii) (rescaled) tğ‘¡t-distribution with five degrees of freedom, and responses are subsequently generated according to model (1) based on the Normal distribution with identity link , and the Poisson and Gamma distribution with log-link. The regression parameter Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} is drawn uniformly at random from spheres in dimension dğ‘‘d of varying radii âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}. The intercept is taken as Î²0âˆ—=câ‹…âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2superscriptsubscriptğ›½0â‹…ğ‘subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\beta_{0}^{*}=c\cdot\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2} with câˆˆ{0.5,5}ğ‘0.55c\in\{0.5,5\}. The sample size is fixed as n=200ğ‘›200n=200. For each configuration consisting of the distribution of the design matrix, the radius âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}, and the value of Î²0âˆ—superscriptsubscriptğ›½0\beta_{0}^{*}, 1000 replications are performed. In each replication, we evaluate the normalized Hamming distance nâˆ’1â€‹âˆ‘i=1nğ•€â€‹(iâ‰ Ï€^â€‹(i))superscriptğ‘›1superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›ğ•€ğ‘–^ğœ‹ğ‘–n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\mathbb{I}(i\neq\widehat{\pi}(i)), where Ï€^^ğœ‹\widehat{\pi} is the minimizer of (8).

In light of Theorem 3, permutation recovery can be achieved if and only if âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2} is large enough, and specifically for Poisson case, if in addition Î²0âˆ—/âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2superscriptsubscriptğ›½0subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\beta_{0}^{*}/\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2} exceeds a certain threshold. Figure 6 confirms this qualitatively. Furthermore, we note that the distribution of the design does not have a significant impact on the results: all three random design can achieve (at least approximate) permutation recovery given sufficient signal as quantified by âˆ¥Î²âˆ—âˆ¥2subscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥superscriptğ›½2\lVert\beta^{*}\rVert_{2}. Finally, note that for the Gamma distribution, recovery results improve as the shape parameter Î½ğœˆ\nu increases.

4 Comparison to the Lahiri-Larsen & Chambers methods

In this section, we aim to provide a short comparison of the proposed method and an established method whose prototype was proposed in [8] and later extended to a wider class of regression models including generalized linear models [10], and will hence be referred to as the Lahiri-Larsen (LL) method. A closely related approach is due to Chambers [9, 25, 11]. The former turns out to be somewhat easier to analyze in the block-structured permutation setting outlined in Â§Â§\S2.3 that will also be adopted in the sequel. The ultimate goal of our discussion is to delineate scenarios in which the proposed estimator tends to be superior and inferior, respectively, relative to the LL method. Both methods differ noticeably with regard to the assumptions on Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} and the required amount of knowledge about the linkage process, and the regimes of interest differ accordingly.

In a nutshell, the LL method assumes that ğ²=Î âˆ—â€‹ğ²âˆ—ğ²superscriptÎ superscriptğ²\mathbf{y}=\Pi^{*}\mathbf{y}^{*} with ğ²jâˆ—|ğ±jconditionalsuperscriptsubscriptğ²ğ‘—subscriptğ±ğ‘—\mathbf{y}_{j}^{*}|\mathbf{x}_{j}, 1â‰¤jâ‰¤N1ğ‘—ğ‘1\leq j\leq N, following a GLM as specified in Â§Â§\S1.1 and Î âˆ—superscriptÎ \Pi^{*} being a generalized random permutation matrix associated with the map Ï€âˆ—:{1,â€¦,N}â†’{1,â€¦,n}:superscriptğœ‹â†’1â€¦ğ‘1â€¦ğ‘›\pi^{*}:\{1,\ldots,N\}\rightarrow\{1,\ldots,n\} whose (i,j)ğ‘–ğ‘—(i,j)-th entry equals one if Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)=jsuperscriptğœ‹ğ‘–ğ‘—\pi^{*}(i)=j and zero otherwise, 1â‰¤iâ‰¤n,â€‰1â‰¤jâ‰¤Nformulae-sequence1ğ‘–ğ‘›1ğ‘—ğ‘1\leq i\leq n,\,1\leq j\leq N. The estimator is particularly easy to understand in the setting in which Ï€âˆ—superscriptğœ‹\pi^{*} is a block-structured permutation (N=nğ‘ğ‘›N=n) as discussed in Â§Â§\S2.3 and the additional assumption that for each block Gjsubscriptğºğ‘—G_{j}, the corresponding permutation is chosen uniformly at random. For linear regression with Gaussian errors, the same order additionally holds in a non-asymptotic fashion. Note that in this case, the underlying estimation equation has the closed form solution Î²^LL=(ğ—âŠ¤â€‹ğğ—)âˆ’1â€‹ğ—âŠ¤â€‹ğğ²superscript^ğ›½LLsuperscriptsuperscriptğ—topğğ—1superscriptğ—topğğ²\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}}=(\mathbf{X}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}\mathbf{X})^{-1}\mathbf{X}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}\mathbf{y} and hence Covâ¡(Î²^LL)=Ï•2â€‹(ğ—âŠ¤â€‹ğğ—)âˆ’1=Ï•2â€‹(âˆ‘j=1Knjâ€‹ğ±Â¯jâ€‹ğ±Â¯jâŠ¤)âˆ’1Covsuperscript^ğ›½LLsuperscriptitalic-Ï•2superscriptsuperscriptğ—topğğ—1superscriptitalic-Ï•2superscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘—1ğ¾subscriptğ‘›ğ‘—subscriptÂ¯ğ±ğ‘—superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ±ğ‘—top1\operatorname{Cov}(\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}})=\phi^{2}(\mathbf{X}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}\mathbf{X})^{-1}=\phi^{2}\left(\sum_{j=1}^{K}n_{j}\overline{\mathbf{x}}_{j}\overline{\mathbf{x}}_{j}^{\top}\right)^{-1}. The same expression is obtained from (11) and (12) by using ğ•â€‹(Î²âˆ—)=Ï•2â€‹Idğ•superscriptğ›½superscriptitalic-Ï•2subscriptğ¼ğ‘‘\mathbf{V}(\beta^{*})=\phi^{2}I_{d} and the fact that ğ=ğ2ğsuperscriptğ2\mathbf{Q}=\mathbf{Q}^{2}.

While the above discussion does not provide a comprehensive analysis of the estimator Î²^LLsuperscript^ğ›½LL\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}} given the focus on a specific choice of ğğ\mathbf{Q} in the setting of a block-structured permutation, we feel that this very choice is presumably among the most relevant in practice. In their landmark paper [8], Lahiri and Larsen consider the entries of ğğ\mathbf{Q} being taken as the probability that observation iğ‘–i in file Fğ±subscriptğ¹ğ±F_{\mathbf{x}} and observation jğ‘—j in File Fğ²subscriptğ¹ğ²F_{\mathbf{y}} are a match, 1â‰¤i,jâ‰¤nformulae-sequence1ğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘›1\leq i,j\leq n, computed from the Fellegi-Sunter model [2] given a set of comparison variables. However, it is generally not guaranteed that this choice is misspecified. In addition, the LL method only asserts unbiasedness when averaging over random Î âˆ—superscriptÎ \Pi^{*}, whereas in practice, the data analyst has to deal with a merged data set arising from a single realization of Î âˆ—superscriptÎ \Pi^{*}. Choosing ğğ\mathbf{Q} according to (10) based on a uniform-at-random model within blocks avoids these issues, producing an unbiased estimator from the comparison of blocking variables only.

In light of the above findings and discussions, we summarize advantages and disadvantages of the estimator Î²^LLsuperscript^ğ›½LL\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}} in relation to the estimator (5) proposed herein. Advantages.

  • â€¢

    The estimator Î²^LLsuperscript^ğ›½LL\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}} does not rely on a sparsely occuring mismatches. In fact, Î²^LLsuperscript^ğ›½LL\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}} can tolerate a fraction of mismatches close to one, and is still guaranteed to be unbiased.

  • â€¢

    Asymptotic confidence intervals can be obtained from the expression for the asymptotic covariance (11).

  • â€¢

    The approach is free of tuning parameters.

Disadvantages.

  • â€¢

    The approach can suffer from a high variance, and is generally not guaranteed to be consistent as the sample size nğ‘›n grows. Instead, consistency requires that the number of blocks Kâ†’âˆâ†’ğ¾K\rightarrow\infty. Even if the latter holds true, the asymptotic rate of convergence Oğâ€‹(Kâˆ’1)subscriptğ‘‚ğsuperscriptğ¾1O_{\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}}(K^{-1}) is suboptimal unless n/K=Oâ€‹(1)ğ‘›ğ¾ğ‘‚1n/K=O(1).

  • â€¢

    In view of the previous bullet, Î²^LLsuperscript^ğ›½LL\widehat{\beta}^{\text{LL}} hinges on the availability of additional information that gives rise to a sufficiently fine block partitioning (i.e., consisting of a good number of blocks).

  • â€¢

    The approach does not account for potential errors in variables used to generate the block partitioning (cf., e.g., [59]).

  • â€¢

    The estimation equation (9) is not guaranteed to have a unique root, and thus practical algorithms for its solution such as Newtonâ€™s method may deliver roots that are not consistent.

Chambersâ€™ method. For the sake of completeness, we present a brief account of the approach due to Chambers in relation to the LL method. Chambersâ€™ method is based on the estimating equation

ğ—âŠ¤â€‹(ğ²âˆ’ğâ€‹ğâˆ—â€‹(Î²))=ğŸ,superscriptğ—topğ²ğsuperscriptğğ›½0\mathbf{X}^{\top}(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{Q}\bm{\mu}^{*}(\beta))=\mathbf{0}, (13)

which differs from the LL estimation equation (9) only in that ğğ—ğğ—\mathbf{Q}\mathbf{X} is replaced by ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X}. Estimation equation (13) is unbiased, but the resulting estimator tends to converge at a slower rate than the LL estimator in the block setting discussed above. Using a similar arguments as above, it can be shown that the asymptotic covariance of the Chambers estimator is given by

(ğ—âŠ¤â€‹ğâŠ¤â€‹ğ•â€‹(Î²âˆ—)â€‹ğ—)âˆ’1â€‹(ğ—âŠ¤â€‹Î âˆ—â€‹ğ•â€‹(Î²âˆ—)â€‹Î âˆ—âŠ¤â€‹ğ—+ğšµ)â€‹(ğ—âŠ¤â€‹ğâŠ¤â€‹ğ•â€‹(Î²âˆ—)â€‹ğ—)âˆ’1,superscriptsuperscriptğ—topsuperscriptğtopğ•superscriptğ›½ğ—1superscriptğ—topsuperscriptÎ ğ•superscriptğ›½superscriptÎ absenttopğ—ğšµsuperscriptsuperscriptğ—topsuperscriptğtopğ•superscriptğ›½ğ—1(\mathbf{X}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}^{\top}\mathbf{V}(\beta^{*})\mathbf{X})^{-1}(\mathbf{X}^{\top}\Pi^{*}\mathbf{V}(\beta^{*})\Pi^{*\top}\mathbf{X}+\bm{\Xi})(\mathbf{X}^{\top}\mathbf{Q}^{\top}\mathbf{V}(\beta^{*})\mathbf{X})^{-1}, (14)

for some positive semidefinite matrix ğšµğšµ\bm{\Xi}, and all other quantities are as above. The slower rate of convergence results from the middle matrix. We have

(ğ—âŠ¤â€‹Î âˆ—â€‹ğ•â€‹(Î²âˆ—)â€‹Î âˆ—âŠ¤â€‹ğ—)=âˆ‘i=1nğ±Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)â€‹Ïˆâ€²â€²â€‹(ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—)â€‹ğ±Ï€âˆ—â€‹(i)âŠ¤=Oğâ€‹(n)superscriptğ—topsuperscriptÎ ğ•superscriptğ›½superscriptÎ absenttopğ—superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›subscriptğ±superscriptğœ‹ğ‘–superscriptğœ“â€²â€²superscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½superscriptsubscriptğ±superscriptğœ‹ğ‘–topsubscriptğ‘‚ğğ‘›(\mathbf{X}^{\top}\Pi^{*}\mathbf{V}(\beta^{*})\Pi^{*\top}\mathbf{X})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\mathbf{x}_{\pi^{*}(i)}\psi^{\prime\prime}(\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{*})\mathbf{x}_{\pi^{*}(i)}^{\top}=O_{\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}}(n)

for typical random designs. The two outer matrices in (14) are the same as in the expression for the asymptotic covariance of the LL method as provided in (11) and (12). Using the results for the LL method above then yields that altogether (14) scales as Oğâ€‹(n/K2)subscriptğ‘‚ğğ‘›superscriptğ¾2O_{\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}}(n/K^{2}), which is generally slower than the rate Oğâ€‹(Kâˆ’1)subscriptğ‘‚ğsuperscriptğ¾1O_{\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}}(K^{-1}) of the LL method.

5 Case Study

We consider the bike sharing data available on the UCI machine learning repository [28]. The data set contains seasonal and weather information along with daily counts of rental bikes used between 2011 and 2012 in Washington, DC. The objective is to predict the number of ride-sharing bikes used during any given day (variable count) based on the categorical predictor variables season (spring, summer, fall, winter), year (2011 or 2012), weathersit (describing the weather situation on a given day in four categories from good to highly inclement weather), weekday (Monday through Sunday, numbered 0 to 6) and workingday (binary variable indicating whether a given day is a working day as opposed to a holiday or Saturday/Sunday), as well as the three continuous predictor variables atemp (feeled temperature), hum (a humidity index) and wind (windspeed).

Overall, the data set consists of 731 instances (days). We apply a square root transformation to the response variable count. The transformed response variable is treated as if it followed a Poisson GLM with log-link, which can formally be regarded as a quasi-likelihood approach. The use of the transformation yields substantial improvement in terms of model fit compared to a Poisson model in which the raw counts are used as the response variable.

In order to further improve the fit of the model, we delete observations satisfying one of the following criteria : (1) days affected by an extreme weather condition (e.g., blizzard, hurricane or windstorm), (2) national holidays (including Thanksgiving and Christmas), (3) especially hot days with temperatures exceeding 31.8 degrees Celsius. The resulting thinned data set includes 692 instances that are used to fit the following (Poisson-like) regression model:

In total, the linear predictor consists of 17 terms apart from the intercept including interaction term between season and atemp and between year and atemp.

In order to mimic mismatch error introduced by record linkage, the response variable (count) is put into a separate file that additionally contains varying combinations of variables that are used for record linkage (see below for a list of those combinations). In order to enforce one-to-one linkage, ties between potentially matching records given the variables used for matching are broken uniformly at random; in order to account for that randomness, we consider 100 independent replications, and the results reported subsequently represent averages over those replications unless noted otherwise. Put differently, the underlying random permutations Î âˆ—superscriptÎ \Pi^{*} are of the block form Î âˆ—=bdiagâ€‹(Î 1âˆ—,â€¦,Î Kâˆ—)superscriptÎ bdiagsubscriptsuperscriptÎ 1â€¦subscriptsuperscriptÎ ğ¾\Pi^{*}=\text{bdiag}(\Pi^{*}_{1},\ldots,\Pi^{*}_{K}), where Kğ¾K denotes the number of unique combinations of values assumed for the matching variables. The average fraction of mismatches k/nğ‘˜ğ‘›k/n obtained in this way approximately equals 0.230.230.23. Figure 7 illustrates the discrepancy between actual response and response after linkage based on the following combination of matching variables: month, holiday, weekday, workingday, temp555temp denotes the temperature in degree Celsius on a given day (integer-valued).. In practice, the combination of variables used for matching may not be (fully) disclosed to the data analyst that operates on the merged data. Therefore, in addition to the case in which the matching variables are fully known, we also consider cases in which only one or two of the matching variables out of five overall are known (cf.Â Table 6).

Results. In order to assess the performance of the proposed approach and the baseline competitors discussed in Â§Â§\S4, estimation of the regression parameters of model (5) is performed based on the merged file contaminated by mismatch error. The resulting parameter estimates are then used to evaluate the deviance on the file {(ğ±i,yiâˆ—)}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{(\mathbf{x}_{i},y_{i}^{*})\}_{i=1}^{n} containing predictors and response in their correct correspondence, i.e.,

2â€‹âˆ‘i=1n[yiâˆ—â€‹logâ¡(yiâˆ—Î¼iest)âˆ’(yiâˆ—âˆ’Î¼iest)],whereâ€‹Î¼itest=expâ¡(Î²0est+ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²est),2superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘›delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–estsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–estwheresuperscriptsubscriptğœ‡ğ‘–testsuperscriptsubscriptğ›½0estsuperscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–topsuperscriptğ›½est2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left[y_{i}^{*}\log\left(\frac{y_{i}^{*}}{\mu_{i}^{\text{est}}}\right)-(y_{i}^{*}-\mu_{i}^{\text{est}})\right],\quad\text{where}\;\mu_{i}^{\text{test}}=\exp(\beta_{0}^{\text{est}}+\mathbf{x}_{i}^{\top}\beta^{\text{est}}), (16)

where Î²estsuperscriptğ›½est\beta^{\text{est}} is a placeholder for the estimates based on the merged file {(ğ±i,yi)}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–subscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{(\mathbf{x}_{i},y_{i})\}_{i=1}^{n} delivered by i) the proposed method, ii) the methods of Lahiri-Larsen (LL) and Chambers, and (iii) the naive estimator without any adjustment for mismatches. Both i) and ii) are evaluated for full and only partial knowledge of the matching variables. The ultimate reference for the quantity (16) is obtained by substituting Î²est=Î²^oraclesuperscriptğ›½estsuperscript^ğ›½oracle\beta^{\text{est}}=\widehat{\beta}^{\text{oracle}}, where the oracle refers to the estimator based on the file {(ğ±i,yiâˆ—)}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{(\mathbf{x}_{i},y_{i}^{*})\}_{i=1}^{n} without any mismatched pairs. The quantity (16) is hence intended to measure the drop in model fit that is induced by parameter estimates in the presence of mismatch error.

Specific figures regarding (16) are presented in Table 6. Note that in case that all matching variables are known to the data analyst, the performance of the LL estimator is rather close to the oracle and better than that of the proposed estimator (6) in its constrained form (265.46 vs.Â 269.92 with a standard error of 0.21). However, as less information about matching variables is available, the proposed estimator performs on par (2nd column) respectively dramatically better (3rd column) than the LL estimator; in the latter case, the performance of the LL estimator is even considerably worse than that of the naive estimator. This is somewhat in alignment with what is predicted in Â§Â§\S4: as the number of blocks Kğ¾K drops, so does the performance of the LL estimator. By contrast, the proposed estimator achieves a solid improvement over the naive estimator even in the complete absence of information about the matching variables used. The Chambers estimator performs weaker than the proposed and the LL estimator if the full set of matching variables is provided; in the two other cases with less information, we experience numerical difficulties (hence the value NA): Newton iterations used to obtain a root of the estimating equations (13) converge to far suboptimal points leading to a deviance exceeding that of the intercept-only model.

Regarding the selection of the tuning parameter Î»ğœ†\lambda for the proposed approach, we create a separate validation set free of mismatches whose size is 20% of the total number of samples, and select Î»ğœ†\lambda so as to minimize the counterpart to (16) on the validation set. Note that the existence of such a validation set is reasonably realistic, at least if sufficient information about matching variables is provided and at least some of the resulting combinations are unique, i.e., they yield singleton blocks for which mismatches can be ruled out. The corresponding results based on this data-driven selection of Î»ğœ†\lambda are labelled â€œProposed(Î»ğœ†\lambda)â€ in Table 6, to be distinguished from â€œProposed(oracle)â€ in which Î»ğœ†\lambda is optimized to minimize the performance measure (16) directly. We note that the performance of â€œProposed(Î»ğœ†\lambda)â€ is only slightly inferior to that of â€œProposed(oracle)â€.

Permutation Recovery. In this paragraph, we describe how the proposed approach can be leveraged to reduce mismatch error in the response variable contained in the merged file. We henceforth suppose that the data analyst is equipped with full knowledge of the matching variables month, holiday, weekday, workingday, temp used during the creation of the merged file. For ease of presentation, we here confine ourselves to two specific random permutations Î minsubscriptÎ \Pi_{\min} and Î maxsubscriptÎ \Pi_{\max} out of the ensemble {Î (1),â€¦,Î (100)}superscriptÎ 1â€¦superscriptÎ 100\{\Pi^{(1)},\ldots,\Pi^{(100)}\} that were generated, defined by

Î min=min1â‰¤iâ‰¤Nâˆ¥Î (i)ğ²âˆ—âˆ’ğ²âˆ—âˆ¥2,Î max=max1â‰¤iâ‰¤Nâˆ¥Î (i)ğ²âˆ—âˆ’ğ²âˆ—âˆ¥2,\Pi_{\min}=\min_{1\leq i\leq N}\lVert\Pi^{(i)}\mathbf{y}^{*}-\mathbf{y}^{*}\rVert_{2},\qquad\Pi_{\max}=\max_{1\leq i\leq N}\lVert\Pi^{(i)}\mathbf{y}^{*}-\mathbf{y}^{*}\rVert_{2},

representing a best and a worst case scenario, respectively. Given (ğ—,Î minâ€‹ğ²âˆ—)ğ—subscriptÎ superscriptğ²(\mathbf{X},\Pi_{\min}\mathbf{y}^{*}) and (ğ—,Î maxâ€‹ğ²âˆ—)ğ—subscriptÎ superscriptğ²(\mathbf{X},\Pi_{\max}\mathbf{y}^{*}), we compute the proposed estimator with constraint matrix ğ‚=ğ‚1ğ‚superscriptğ‚1\mathbf{C}=\mathbf{C}^{1} (cf.Â Table 6 top) and use the resulting solution Î²^^ğ›½\widehat{\beta} in place of Î²âˆ—superscriptğ›½\beta^{*} in the optimization problem defining the maximum likelihood estimator for the unknown permutation (8). The resulting optimization problem is given by

minÎ âˆˆğ’«â€‹(ğ’¢)âˆ’âŸ¨Î â€‹ğ²,ğ—â€‹Î²^âŸ©,subscriptÎ ğ’«ğ’¢Î ğ²ğ—^ğ›½\min_{\Pi\in\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{G})}-\langle\Pi\mathbf{y},\mathbf{X}\widehat{\beta}\rangle, (17)

where ğ²=Î minâ€‹ğ²âˆ—ğ²subscriptÎ superscriptğ²\mathbf{y}=\Pi_{\min}\mathbf{y}^{*} and ğ²=Î maxâ€‹ğ²âˆ—ğ²subscriptÎ superscriptğ²\mathbf{y}=\Pi_{\max}\mathbf{y}^{*}, respectively, and ğ’«â€‹(ğ’¢)ğ’«ğ’¢\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{G}) denotes the set of all block-wise permutation matrices induced by the resulting index subsets ğ’¢={Gj}j=1Kğ’¢superscriptsubscriptsubscriptğºğ‘—ğ‘—1ğ¾\mathcal{G}=\{G_{j}\}_{j=1}^{K}, K=535ğ¾535K=535, corresponding to identical values for the matching variables. Note that the minimizer of (17) can be obtained by pairing the order statistics of the linear predictor and the response within each of the sets {Gj}j=1Ksuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğºğ‘—ğ‘—1ğ¾\{G_{j}\}_{j=1}^{K}. While permutation recovery, i.e., {Î ^=Î min}^Î subscriptÎ \{\widehat{\Pi}=\Pi_{\min}\} and {Î ^=Î max}^Î subscriptÎ \{\widehat{\Pi}=\Pi_{\max}\}, respectively, where Î ^^Î \widehat{\Pi} denotes the minimizer of (17) turns out to be out of reach here, a substantial reduction in mismatch error is achieved, i.e., Î ^â€‹ğ²^Î ğ²\widehat{\Pi}\mathbf{y} is visibly closer to ğ²âˆ—superscriptğ²\mathbf{y}^{*} than ğ²ğ²\mathbf{y} as shown in Figure 8. The corrected response Î ^â€‹ğ²^Î ğ²\widehat{\Pi}\mathbf{y} can be used to refit the regression model. Figure 8 indicates that the resulting fitted values exhibit a much better agreement with the fitted values obtained from a mismatch-free data set.

6 Conclusion

In this paper, we have presented a method based on â„“1subscriptâ„“1\ell_{1}-penalization to account for mismatch error in the response in linked files, and have highlighted its benefits compared to established methods for this scenario. We have also explored how to directly reduce mismatch error by estimating the underlying permutation associated with the true correspondence between predictor-response pairs. The proposed approach is computationally appealing, supported by theoretical guarantees, and bears considerable potential regarding the adjustment for mismatch error in post-linkage analysis. At the same time, the approach presented herein prompts several directions of future research. Concerning the estimation of the regression parameter, it is worthwhile exploring the use of observation-specific penalization factors {Î»i}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğœ†ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{\lambda_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n} instead of a single global value Î»ğœ†\lambda that could prove particularly beneficial in Poisson and Gamma regression in light of heteroscedasticity. Moreover, it is of great practical relevance to be able to conduct statistical inference for the regression parameter (confidence intervals and tests of linear hypotheses). A promising approach with regard to this aspect is the use of techniques developed for constructing confidence intervals in lasso regression, e.g., [60, 61, 62].

Concerning estimation of the permutation, we have focused on exact permutation recovery and on approximate recovery with small Hamming distance. The results are coupled to stringent conditions, which are often not met in practice. Nevertheless, the results presented in the case study of the previous section indicate that approximate permutation recovery can be achieved with respect to alternative metrics like the â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2}-distance between the true response ğ²âˆ—superscriptğ²\mathbf{y}^{*} and the estimator Î ^â€‹ğ²^Î ğ²\widehat{\Pi}\mathbf{y}, and elaborating the corresponding theory constitutes a further promising direction.

Appendix C Proof of Theorem 3

Since the {ğ±i}i=1nsuperscriptsubscriptsubscriptğ±ğ‘–ğ‘–1ğ‘›\{\mathbf{x}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n} are now considered random, we may no longer assume without loss of generality that Î¼1â‰¤â€¦â‰¤Î¼nsubscriptğœ‡1â€¦subscriptğœ‡ğ‘›\mu_{1}\leq\ldots\leq\mu_{n}. Instead, the proof now involves a union bound over (n2)binomialğ‘›2\binom{n}{2} pairs:

ğâ¡(Ï€^â‰ Ï€âˆ—|ğ—)ğ^ğœ‹conditionalsuperscriptğœ‹ğ—\displaystyle\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\hat{\pi}\neq\pi^{*}|\mathbf{X}) =2â€‹ğâ¡(â‹ƒi<j{Yi>Yjâˆ£ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—<ğ±jâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—})absent2ğsubscriptğ‘–ğ‘—conditional-setsubscriptğ‘Œğ‘–subscriptğ‘Œğ‘—subscriptsuperscriptğ±topğ‘–superscriptğ›½subscriptsuperscriptğ±topğ‘—superscriptğ›½\displaystyle=2\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}\left(\bigcup_{i<j}\left\{Y_{i}>Y_{j}\mid\mathbf{x}^{\top}_{i}\beta^{*}<\mathbf{x}^{\top}_{j}\beta^{*}\right\}\right)
â‰¤2â€‹âˆ‘i<jğâ¡(Yi>Yjâˆ£ğ±iâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—<ğ±jâŠ¤â€‹Î²âˆ—)absent2subscriptğ‘–ğ‘—ğsubscriptğ‘Œğ‘–conditionalsubscriptğ‘Œğ‘—subscriptsuperscriptğ±topğ‘–superscriptğ›½subscriptsuperscriptğ±topğ‘—superscriptğ›½\displaystyle\leq 2\sum_{i<j}\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(Y_{i}>Y_{j}\mid\mathbf{x}^{\top}_{i}\beta^{*}<\mathbf{x}^{\top}_{j}\beta^{*})

Accordingly, we state the following Lemma B.1 which arises as a modification of Theorem 2. The proof of the latter can be carried over easily since the only the union bound changes while the individual terms inside the sum can be estimated in the same way as before; therefore, the proof of the subsequent lemma is omitted.

Lemma B. 1.

Consider the MLE Ï€^^ğœ‹\widehat{\pi} given by the minimizer of (8). For any Î´>0ğ›¿0\delta>0, we have ğâ¡(Ï€^â‰ Ï€âˆ—|ğ—)<Î´ğ^ğœ‹conditionalsuperscriptğœ‹ğ—ğ›¿\operatorname{\mathbf{P}}(\widehat{\pi}\neq\pi^{*}|\mathbf{X})<\delta if

  • (a)
